@ETSshow @bananaP08 @fumikochino @DrMalikaSiker Preparing for simulation is another story, but also dependent upon acuity & need for complex planning. I range from no imaging (superficial/ortho) to everything must be ready/coordinated (stereotactic). 3/

@ETSshow @bananaP08 @fumikochino @DrMalikaSiker Referring MDs determine the urgency of the consult, & we try to see them accordingly. If non-urgent it's reasonable to wait a bit for imaging. But I worry more about delaying someone who needed to be seen sooner & it's not non-clinical staff's job to clinically assess acuity. 2/

@ETSshow @bananaP08 @fumikochino @DrMalikaSiker I take care of many patients with a significant number of outside scans, so our admin staff is usually quite good getting them before simulation. That said, I pre-review imaging and email staff before clinic starts to make sure they know if something key is missing. 1/

MRIs more routine and more biologic data in core bx. 1/

Off protocol, not sure. I agree that genomics may have value, but only if additive to other factors. We can optimize those possibly without the test from data we already get.
